---
import CaseStudy from '../../layouts/CaseStudy.astro';
---

<CaseStudy
  title="Migrating an engineering org from Jira to Linear"
  eyebrow="Branch · Spring 2026"
  summary="A six-week pilot with real Branch engineers. Not a vendor demo. The data made the case. 2.7× throughput per engineer, 87 to 93% cycle completion against Linear's 87% benchmark, and 6 of 7 engineers strongly recommending migration."
  role="Sr. Director of Product Experience"
  duration="12 weeks (setup and pilot)"
  team="Eng, PM, Product Ops"
  outcome="$42K cost reduction. 300+ seats."
>
  <h2>The problem wasn't Jira. It was the cost of fixing Jira.</h2>

  <p>
    Branch was running on Jira at a real cost. 398 licenses, 62 spaces, with 30 of them
    abandoned or inactive. Issue types, workflows, and fields were non-standardized
    across every team. Epics couldn't span team boundaries, so cross-team initiative
    visibility didn't exist. The tool was failing despite full adoption.
  </p>

  <p>
    The proposed remediation, call it Jira 2.0, required an outside contractor and months
    of internal cleanup. Before signing off, I wanted to test a different question:
    <strong>
      should we invest the Jira 2.0 remediation effort into fixing Jira, or into a
      platform that doesn't need fixing?
    </strong>
  </p>

  <h2>A real test, not a vendor demo</h2>

  <p>
    I designed a six-week live pilot. Not a sandbox, not a sales engineering walkthrough.
    Real Branch engineers, real work, the same engineers benchmarked in both systems.
  </p>

  <ul class="list-none pl-0 my-8 space-y-3">
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Teams:</strong> Engagement (Eng + PM), Product Documentation, Pinx Panthers, Auxin</span>
    </li>
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Method:</strong> Before survey (Jira baseline), mid-cycle check-in, post-pilot final survey</span>
    </li>
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Benchmark:</strong> Before and after issue data from the same 7 engineers in both Jira and Linear</span>
    </li>
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Integrations:</strong> Slack agent, GitHub, Claude Code MCP, Windsurf, DX</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    I set five target metrics before the pilot started and held the team accountable to
    them. Issue creation frequency, engineer satisfaction, cycle completion rate,
    percentage of work tracked, and issue resolution time. I also met with Linear's SE
    team to address concerns from internal dissenters before the cutover decision.
  </p>

  <!-- Big stat callout -->
  <div class="not-prose my-16 py-16 px-8 md:px-12 bg-navy-deep text-cream relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="absolute top-6 left-8 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-cream/60">
      The Result
    </div>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
      <div>
        <p class="font-display text-[clamp(5rem,15vw,12rem)] leading-none text-orange">
          2.7×
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl text-cream leading-tight mb-4">
          More issues completed per engineer per week in Linear vs. Jira.
        </p>
        <p class="font-mono text-sm text-cream/70">
          Same 7 engineers. Same work. Source: Jira "Status Category Changed" field and
          Linear export. Linear's cross-customer benchmark is 2×. Branch hit 2.7×.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Five metrics. Four hits. One partial. Zero misses.</h2>

  <p>The pilot delivered against every target I set:</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-12 space-y-4">
    {[
      {
        metric: 'Issue creation frequency',
        target: 'Target: 2× increase',
        result: '2.7× throughput (Jira 2.42/eng/wk to Linear 6.47/eng/wk)',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: 'Engineer satisfaction',
        target: 'Target: 4.0+ in Linear',
        result: '5.0/5 overall. Every dimension above 4.0.',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: 'Cycle completion rate',
        target: 'Target: stable or improved',
        result: '100%, 87%, 93% across first three cycles. Planning 4 cycles ahead.',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: '% of work tracked',
        target: 'Target: 80%+',
        result: '4 of 5 respondents at 75 to 100%. 86% of issues tied to a project.',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: 'Issue resolution time',
        target: 'Target: 3.3× faster',
        result: 'Median work time in Linear: 1.9 days. Jira baseline unavailable in export.',
        status: 'PARTIAL',
      },
    ].map((row) => (
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-4 py-5 border-b border-ink/10 items-start">
        <div class="md:col-span-3">
          <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink">{row.metric}</p>
          <p class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-muted mt-1">{row.target}</p>
        </div>
        <div class="md:col-span-7 text-ink-soft">{row.result}</div>
        <div class="md:col-span-2 md:text-right">
          <span
            class={`font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] px-3 py-1 ${
              row.status === 'HIT' ? 'bg-orange text-cream' : 'bg-cream-deep text-ink'
            }`}
          >
            {row.status}
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Every engineer improved. Even the one who preferred Jira.</h2>

  <p>
    Throughput gains weren't concentrated in early adopters or power users. Each of the
    seven pilot engineers measured higher issue completion in Linear than in Jira,
    ranging from 1.2× to 7.0× per individual. The engineer who rated Linear lowest in
    mid-pilot still completed more work in it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Survey deltas told the same story. Across every dimension I measured (ease of
    creation, ability to triage, trust in the data, roadmap visibility, manager
    visibility, overall satisfaction) Linear improved on Jira. Overall satisfaction
    swung from 2.83 to 5.00, the largest delta in the survey.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "Please let us keep using Linear. I desperately do not want to go back to Jira."
    <br />
    <span class="not-italic font-mono text-sm text-ink-muted">
      Engagement team engineer, post-pilot survey
    </span>
  </blockquote>

  <h2>The capability decision behind the cost decision</h2>

  <p>
    The financial case wasn't a savings story. It was a capability story. Three scenarios
    on the table:
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-10 grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
    <div class="p-6 border border-ink/15 bg-cream-warm">
      <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Stay · Fix Jira</p>
      <p class="font-display text-3xl text-ink mb-2">$173K+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-soft">
        Jira + Confluence + Asana. Plus Jira 2.0 remediation cost (TBD, contractor required).
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 border border-ink/15 bg-cream-warm">
      <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Switch · Replace Jira</p>
      <p class="font-display text-3xl text-ink mb-2">$177K</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-soft">
        Linear + Notion + Asana unchanged. No remediation cost.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-6 border-2 border-orange bg-orange/5">
      <p class="eyebrow mb-3 text-orange-deep">Recommended</p>
      <p class="font-display text-3xl text-ink mb-2">$131K</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-soft">
        Linear + Notion. Asana removed pending parallel evaluation. <strong>$42K reduction.</strong>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    The 2.7× throughput was measured before any of the integrations activated. Gong
    (10,000 customer calls per year converting to issues automatically), Zendesk Triage,
    Linear Asks (replacing Branch Assist for IT provisioning), and Linear Releases for
    CI/CD. The pilot result was the floor, not the ceiling.
  </p>

  <h2>What I did, what changed</h2>

  <p>
    I owned the end-to-end pilot. Design, execution, and recommendation. JQL-scoped sprint
    exports from Jira, CSV mapping logic for the import, importer evaluation across
    Linear's native Jira assistant and CLI paths, pilot team selection, benchmark
    methodology, before and after survey design, dissenter review meetings, and the
    final executive recommendation.
  </p>

  <p>
    The migration moved forward as a full org cut-over with white-glove onboarding from
    Linear's customer success team. Sequenced first through Engineering and Product, then
    IT and Security, then CX and Sales. Asana evaluated in parallel for the remaining
    30-day decision window.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this case study</h2>

  <p>
    Most "design leader leads tooling decision" stories are project-management fables.
    This one shows what design leadership actually looks like at the executive level.
    Framing the right question (capability vs. cost). Designing a defensible test
    methodology. Holding the test accountable to pre-set metrics. Presenting the result
    as a business case rather than a feature wishlist. Managing the dissent that
    inevitably surfaces when the data is too good.
  </p>

  <p>
    Design leadership isn't just about what ships. It's about what gets decided.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
